ow they came to terms with a new land and with their new neighbours, including other Mennonites, Ukrainians, French Canadians, and Indigenous Peoples. The book discusses the impact of the Great Depression and how the immigrants struggled with their identity in Canada as Hitler and Stalin rose to power in Germany and the USSR. It reveals the immigrants’ desire to maintain their faith, language, and culture while encouraging their children to take advantage of an education conducted mainly in English. On Stony Ground explores how prosperity following the Second World War helped the immigrants to build a community in conjunction with others, including Mennonites and non-Mennonites, and to accept their new home in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Mennonite.2bisacsh  aCanada.  aGrunthal.  aHitler.  aManitoba.  aMennonite.  aRussia.  aRussländer Mennonites.  aStalin.  aUkraine.  aethnic studies.  aethnicity.  aethnography.  ahistory of Mennonites in Canada.  ahistory.  aimmigrants.  aimmigration.  aprairies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079737440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148754741740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487547417423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487547417/original  a978-3-11-079737-4  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles